              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- HTTP API -->
        <div class="docs-block">
          <h3 id="api">HTTP API</h3>
          <p>
            The bot exposes a REST API at <code>api.stoatcord.com</code>.
            Public endpoints like <code>/api/diag</code> require no auth.
            Archive endpoints require a per-guild Bearer token (get it with <code>/token</code> in Discord).
          </p>

          <h4>Public Endpoints</h4>
          <div class="docs-table-wrap">
            <table class="docs-table">
              <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Path</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td><code>GET</code></td><td><code>/api/diag</code></td><td>Bot health &amp; diagnostics</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>GET</code></td><td><code>/api/push/vapid</code></td><td>VAPID public key for WebPush</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <h4>Archive Endpoints (Bearer token required)</h4>
          <div class="code-block"><pre><code><span class="code-comment"># Get your token from Discord</span>
/token

<span class="code-comment"># Check archive status</span>
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN" \
  https://api.stoatcord.com/api/archive/status

<span class="code-comment"># Start an export</span>
curl -X POST \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"discordChannelId":"123456789"}' \
  https://api.stoatcord.com/api/archive/start

<span class="code-comment"># Pause / Resume</span>
curl -X POST \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"jobId":"abc12345"}' \
  https://api.stoatcord.com/api/archive/pause</code></pre></div>

          <h4>Push Registration</h4>
          <div class="docs-table-wrap">
            <table class="docs-table">
              <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Path</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td><code>POST</code></td><td><code>/api/push/register</code></td><td>Register a device for push (FCM or WebPush)</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>DELETE</code></td><td><code>/api/push/unregister</code></td><td>Remove a device registration</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>GET</code></td><td><code>/api/push/status?deviceId=…</code></td><td>Check device registration status</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Masquerade -->
        <div class="docs-block">
          <h3 id="masquerade">How Masquerade Works</h3>
          <p>
            When messages cross the bridge, the bot uses platform-native impersonation
            to preserve the original sender's identity:
          </p>
          <ul class="docs-list">
            <li><strong>Discord → Stoat:</strong> Messages are sent via the Stoat <code>masquerade</code> API field, which displays the Discord user's name and avatar on the Stoat message. The message is owned by the bot but renders as the original user.</li>
            <li><strong>Stoat → Discord:</strong> Messages are sent via a Discord webhook, which can set an arbitrary username and avatar URL. The message appears as the Stoat user.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Neither method grants the bot access to the impersonated user's account or permissions.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

